</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="78" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,1810,1982]" pageId="3" pageNumber="78">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,274,1810,1836]" pageId="3" pageNumber="78">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
This species is most similar to 
<taxonomicName authority="Liu &amp; Wang &amp; Guo &amp; Chen &amp; Wang, 2022" authorityName="Liu &amp; Wang &amp; Guo &amp; Chen &amp; Wang" authorityYear="2022" box="[624,743,1811,1837]" class="Insecta" family="Coccinellidae" genus="Sulcolotis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="78" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="threadis" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[624,743,1811,1837]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="78">S. threadis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[750,839,1811,1837]" pageId="3" pageNumber="78">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[750,839,1811,1837]" pageId="3" pageNumber="78" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
in external appearance but can be distinguished from the latter by the penis guide shorter than parameres. In 
<taxonomicName authority="Liu &amp; Wang &amp; Guo &amp; Chen &amp; Wang, 2022" authorityName="Liu &amp; Wang &amp; Guo &amp; Chen &amp; Wang" authorityYear="2022" box="[791,913,1847,1873]" class="Insecta" family="Coccinellidae" genus="Sulcolotis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="78" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="threadis" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[791,913,1847,1873]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="78">S. threadis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[922,1014,1847,1873]" pageId="3" pageNumber="78">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[922,1014,1847,1873]" pageId="3" pageNumber="78" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
, the penis guide is nearly as long as parameres in lateral view.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="4" lastPageNumber="79" pageId="3" pageNumber="78" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,1810,1982]" pageId="3" pageNumber="78">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,345,1918,1944]" pageId="3" pageNumber="78">Description.</emphasis>
TL: 
<quantity box="[407,565,1919,1945]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.745" metricValueMax="2.86" metricValueMin="2.63" pageId="3" pageNumber="78" unit="mm" value="2.745" valueMax="2.86" valueMin="2.63">2.63–2.86mm</quantity>
, TW: 
<quantity box="[640,799,1919,1945]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.315" metricValueMax="2.37" metricValueMin="2.26" pageId="3" pageNumber="78" unit="mm" value="2.315" valueMax="2.37" valueMin="2.26">2.26–2.37mm</quantity>
, TH: 
<quantity box="[869,1027,1919,1946]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.48" metricValueMax="1.59" metricValueMin="1.37" pageId="3" pageNumber="78" unit="mm" value="1.48" valueMax="1.59" valueMin="1.37">1.37–1.59mm</quantity>
, TL/TW: 1.16–1.21, PL/PW: 0.28– 0.30, EL/EW: 0.94–0.99, HW/PW: 0.56–0.58, PW/TW: 0.63–0.64, HW/TW: 0.35–0.37, Eye W/HW: 0.43–0.46.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,151,681]" pageId="4" pageNumber="79">Head reddish brown. Elytra reddish brown with a long ovate black spot situated at 1/3 elytral length to base. Underside yellowish brown, except metaventrite and the middle part of the first abdominal ventrite reddish brown.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,151,681]" pageId="4" pageNumber="79">
Body rounded, weakly convex, shiny and glabrous. Eyes finely faceted, interocular distance 0.45 times width of head. Frons broad with irregular transparent spots, punctures uniform and dense (
<figureCitation box="[1093,1174,259,285]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1716,1740]" captionTargetBox="[160,1427,713,1683]" captionTargetId="figure-211@4.[151,1436,705,1693]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 3. Sulcolotis ovalis Liu et Wang sp. n.: a) dorsal habitus; b. lateral habitus; c. frontal habitus; d. tegmen, ventral view; e. tegmen, lateral view; f. penis; g. part of abdomen, male." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6876475" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6876475/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="79">Fig. 3c</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,151,681]" pageId="4" pageNumber="79">
Pronotum 0.64 times of elytral width (PW/TW=1:1.6), moderately transverse, punctures uniform and dense (
<figureCitation box="[159,240,331,357]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1716,1740]" captionTargetBox="[160,1427,713,1683]" captionTargetId="figure-211@4.[151,1436,705,1693]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 3. Sulcolotis ovalis Liu et Wang sp. n.: a) dorsal habitus; b. lateral habitus; c. frontal habitus; d. tegmen, ventral view; e. tegmen, lateral view; f. penis; g. part of abdomen, male." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6876475" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6876475/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="79">Fig. 3c</figureCitation>
). Elytra with uniform and dense punctures (
<figureCitation box="[733,846,331,357]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1716,1740]" captionTargetBox="[160,1427,713,1683]" captionTargetId="figure-211@4.[151,1436,705,1693]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 3. Sulcolotis ovalis Liu et Wang sp. n.: a) dorsal habitus; b. lateral habitus; c. frontal habitus; d. tegmen, ventral view; e. tegmen, lateral view; f. penis; g. part of abdomen, male." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6876475" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6876475/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="79">Figs 3a–c</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,151,681]" box="[199,957,367,393]" pageId="4" pageNumber="79">
Ventrite 6 subhemisphenical and ventrite 7 nearly straight (
<figureCitation box="[861,944,367,393]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1716,1740]" captionTargetBox="[160,1427,713,1683]" captionTargetId="figure-211@4.[151,1436,705,1693]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 3. Sulcolotis ovalis Liu et Wang sp. n.: a) dorsal habitus; b. lateral habitus; c. frontal habitus; d. tegmen, ventral view; e. tegmen, lateral view; f. penis; g. part of abdomen, male." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6876475" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6876475/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="79">
Fig. 
<quantity box="[913,944,367,393]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="kg" metricValue="3.0" pageId="4" pageNumber="79" unit="g" value="3.0">3g</quantity>
</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,151,681]" pageId="4" pageNumber="79">Male genitalia: penis relatively short and slender, apex pointed, penis capsule with nearly same length of inner arm and outer arm. Tegmen with penis guide in lateral view slender, widest at base, narrowing to apex, distinctly shorter than parameres.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
